ce:section.ce:para:
The detailed surface and structural analysis of C-dots synthesized from F. benghalensis and F. religiosa L extracts were reported previously from our laboratory [16]. In brief, the pristine C-dots were spherical with a particle of 2.4 nm and a zeta potential of −20 mV. No distinctive lattice structure was visible in HRTEM images, which revealed the amorphous nature of the particle. UV–Visible spectra show an absorbance peak at 317 nm, which corresponds to C-dots, and a peak at 280 nm, which is caused by the π – π* transition of aromatic amino acids in the protein contained in the leaf extract. C-dots PLE spectrum generated by exciting the C-dots at 317 nm. The emission peak is shown at 455 nm in the green area of the absorption spectrum, following the blue-green luminescence of C-dots. Its enhanced PLE intensity is the only significant difference we noticed in the C-dots prepared from F. religiosa L. PLE intensity of C-dots prepared from F. benghalensis was ∼ 150 a.u., whereas the PLE intensity of C-dots prepared from F. religiosa was ∼ 362.5 a.u. After surface functionalization, TC-dots maintained their PLE (∼ 362.5 a.u.), whereas AC-dots quenched PLE significantly (∼ 62 a.u.). The FTIR analysis confirmed the successful surface functionalization of C-dots (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). In TC-dots, the sharp peak at 2550 cm−1 indicated the thiol group (-SH) present on its surface. After acid functionalization, the surface of AC-dots is occupied with oxygen-containing functional moieties such as –COOH (1740 cm−1), -C = O (1350 cm−1), and –OH (3570 cm−1).

Biogenic C-dots display a quick responsible character with analytes to produce molecular logic circuits with exceptional stability. Upon this, we have designed a logic library with 15 basic logic gates (Scheme. 1
                        ) and their combinations by integrating the three lead platforms of C-dots with other analytes such as Fe3+, Hg2+, AA, Glu, DV, and H2O2. Initially, a NOT logic gate is created when the C-dots are selectively quenched in the presence of Fe3+, also known as an inverter (
                           Fig. S2

                        ). A NOT gate is TRUE only when its input signal is FALSE. However, adding AA to C-dots enhanced PLE, which led to the construction of the PASS1 gate, whose output is always TRUE (
                           Fig. S2

                        ) 
                        [11].

On the other hand, the addition of DV in the C-dots platform opens up two more possibilities. In the first case, Fe3+ and DV are integrated to obtain a NOT gate (
                           Fig. S3
                        ) [20]. Here, entries (0,0) and (1,0) showed PLE enhancement, while entries (0,1) and (1,1) showed the output has quenched. In the second scenario, AA and DV were taken as the inputs, and there was no significant change in the PLE signal (Fig. 1B). According to the truth table, in the absence of both inputs (entry 0,0), the output remains the same (output = 1). In entry (0,1), the PLE enhances, resulting output = 1. However, in the presence of DV (entry 1,0), the C-dots have negligible changes producing an output = 1. The output PLE enhances two folds generating PASS1 logic operation in both inputs (entry 1,1). According to the molecular library, three basic platforms were designed. Initially, C-dots were synthesized from a biogenic precursor, which was later modified with dithiothreitol (DDT), known as thiol-functionalized C-dots (TC-dots), and treated with HNO3, known as acid-functionalized C-dots (AC-dots).

Furthermore, the C-dots are modified with DDT to generate stable TC-dots, accompanied by PASS1 logic operation (
                           Fig. S2
                        ) [21]. However, the TC-dots are masked with the thiol group which makes a huge difference while integrating logic circuits. The TC-dots can be extensively quenched by the presence of H2O2, hence the thiol group might oxidize upon on addition of H2O2 which results in a NOT logic gate (

                           Fig. S2

                        ). Fe3+ is added to the existing TC-dots system resulting in a NOR gate. Here, H2O2 and Fe3+ were assigned as two inputs to identify the combination state with respect to PLE readouts (Fig. 1C). The NOR gate implies where the output is FALSE only when any of the inputs is TRUE, otherwise the output is TRUE. According to the Boolean expression from the truth table, the PLE intensity was high (output = 1) in the absence of both analytes (entry 0,0).

The PLE signal was quenched in the presence of H2O2 (entry 0,1) or Fe3+ (entry 1,0), resulting in output = 0. However, when both the inputs are present (entry 1,1), the H2O2 and Fe3+ are unable to restore emission intensity (output = 0), necessitating the building of a NOR gate. When Fe3+ and Glu are integrated, a NOT gate is observed (
                           Fig. S4
                        ) and H2O2 is treated with Glu towards TC-dots, which restores the PLE [22,23]. The PLE intensity was strong (output = 1) in the absence of both analytes (entry 0,0) and the presence of Glu (entry 0,1), however, the PLE is quenched in the presence of H2O2 (entry 1,0) and restored when both inputs (entry 1,1) are integrated resulting an IMP logic gate (Fig. 1D).

Nevertheless, the C-dots were accompanied by NOT logic operation by treating with HNO3 to create stable AC-dots (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). The AC-dots are functionalized with the acidic group and reduced the PLE of the core C-dots. On the other hand, the addition of AA significantly increased the PLE of the AC-dots, resulting in the generation of a YES gate (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). The AC-dots system provides the same YES logic operation when Fe3+ and AA are combined (
                           Fig. S5
                        ). The entries (0,0) and (1,0) showed quenching of fluorescence output and entries (0,1) and (1,1) showed an increase in output. However, the AC-dots system remains the same in the presence of Hg2+, thus Hg2+ and AA were assigned as two inputs to identify the combination state with regard to PLE readouts. (Fig. 1E). Therefore, in the absence of both analytes (entry 0,0), the PLE intensity was low (output = 0), as seen in the truth table. The PLE was enhanced in the presence of AA (entry 0,1), resulting in an output of 1, whereas no PLE enhancement was observed in the presence of Hg2+ (entry 1,0), resulting in an output of 0. Here, AA can reduce Hg2+ to Hg, and the state of AC-dots remained unchanged in the presence of AA and Hg2+ 
                        [24]. The PLE intensity remains turned off while both inputs are present (entry 1,1), resulting in output = 0, which yields an INHIBIT (INH) gate, with output following input B if input A is FALSE and otherwise the output is FALSE. Nevertheless, two potential quenchers (Hg2+ and Fe3+) were introduced to the AC-dots platform as the two inputs and there was no significant change in PLE as shown in Fig. 1F. The output remains the same (output = 0) in the absence and presence of both inputs (entry 0,0) and (entry 1,1), according to the truth table. Due to the metal ions in entries (0,1) and (1,0), the AC-dots have further quenched, resulting in an output of 0 and a PASS0 logic operation is created, where the output is always FALSE [11].
